import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
# do pd. [tab] to see functions
# look in google for pandas.pydata.org/docs
# Pandas Series = like np.array
pd_series = pd.Series([10, 100, 15, 35]) # we can put diff types but then the Series will be object. not recommended
np_array = np.array([10, 100, 15, 35])
print(np_array)
print(pd_series)
print(type(pd_series))
# we get a table with index-value, like dictionary. this is thee diff
# we can change from default numbers to seomthing else
data = [1776, 1867, 1821]
label_index = ['USA', 'CANADA', 'MEXICO']
pd_series = pd.Series(data, label_index)
print(pd_series)
print(pd_series['USA']) # this is a unique feature of Pandas
#print(pd_series[0]) #this will show a Warning since the index is string and will not work in future version # use iloc
# see below how to print index 0 using .keys()

# can we append?
# Create an initial Series
original_series = pd.Series([1, 2, 3])
# Append an item (4) to the Series using pd.concat
new_series = pd.concat([original_series, pd.Series([4])], ignore_index=True)
print(new_series)

dict1 = {'USA': 1776, 'CANADA': 1867, 'MEXICO': 1821}
pd_ser_dict = pd.Series(dict1)
print(pd_ser_dict)

pd_keys = pd_series.keys()
print(pd_keys)
print(type(pd_keys))
print(pd_keys[0])
print(pd_keys.size)
print(pd_series[pd_keys[0]])

second = {'Brazil': 1768, 'CHINA': 200, 'USA': 100}
second_ser = pd.Series(second)
concat_ser = pd_ser_dict + second_ser #where it does not appear in both it becomes NaN
print(concat_ser)
concat_ser2 = pd_ser_dict.add(second_ser, fill_value=0) # without fill_value=0 it will look the 2 lines ago
print(concat_ser2)
concat_ser3 = pd_ser_dict.add(second_ser, fill_value=100) 
print(concat_ser3)

In[30]:
print(excel_df.describe()) # only on numbers
  # mean = average
  # std = standard deviation . stiat teken
  # 25% of the number are benieth these number, 50% median, 75% are beieth it

  # 25% (first quartile): This is the median of the first half of the data points. 
  #   If you sort the data in ascending order and split at the middle, the 25% value is the median of the lower half. 
  #   It shows that 25% of the values in each column are below this value.
  # 50% (median): The median value of the data in each column. Half of the data points are above this value and half 
  #   are below. For column 'a', the median is 6.
  # 75% (third quartile): Similar to the 25% value but for the upper half of the data. 
  #   It shows that 75% of the values in each column are below this value, and 25% are above.

"""
    a   b   c   d  calculation
0   0   1   2   3     0.000000
1   4   5   6   7     8.000000
2   8   9  10  11     8.888889
3  12  13  14  15     9.230769
"""
print('========== delete row 2 =======================')
print(excel_df.drop(2, axis=0)) # it does not delete from the original. copy. creates duplicate. axis=0 row axis=1 column
print()
print(excel_df)
print('========== delete row 2 in the original =======================')
excel_df.drop(2, axis=0, inplace=True) # actually deletes row 2
print()
print(excel_df)
print('========== delete row 1 in the original =======================')
excel_df.drop('b', axis=1, inplace=True) # actually deletes column 'b'
print()
print(excel_df)
